# Environment Variables Template
# Copy this to .env.local and fill in your actual values

# ==============================================
# REQUIRED: Weather API
# ==============================================
# Get your free key from: https://openweathermap.org/api
OPENWEATHER_API_KEY=your_openweather_api_key_here

# ==============================================
# OPTIONAL: ML Server URL
# ==============================================
# If deploying Python ML server separately (Railway/Render):
# ML_API_URL=https://your-ml-server-url.com
#
# If not set, app will use fallback rule-based model
# Local development: http://127.0.0.1:8000
ML_API_URL=http://127.0.0.1:8000

# ==============================================
# NOTE: NASA POWER API
# ==============================================
# NASA POWER API is completely FREE and requires NO API KEY!
# We use it for satellite data (NDVI, temperature, precipitation)
# No configuration needed - it just works out of the box
# API Docs: https://power.larc.nasa.gov/docs/

# ==============================================
# PRODUCTION DEPLOYMENT NOTES
# ==============================================
# 1. Never commit .env.local to Git (already in .gitignore)
# 2. Add these variables in Vercel dashboard under Environment Variables:
#    - OPENWEATHER_API_KEY (required)
#    - ML_API_URL (optional - only if deploying ML server)
# 3. NASA POWER API requires no configuration
# 4. Free tier limits:
#    - OpenWeather: 1000 calls/day free
#    - NASA POWER: Unlimited and free forever!
#    - Vercel: Unlimited hobby deployments
